{"copyright": {"licenseType": "NO", "determinationType": "GOV_PUBLIC_USE_PERMITTED", "thirdPartyContentCondition": "NOT_SET"}, "subjectCategories": ["Meteorology and Climatology"], "exportControl": {"isExportControl": "NO", "ear": "NO", "itar": "NO"}, "distributionDate": "2019-07-17T00:00:00.0000000+00:00", "title": "The Future of Satellite-based Lightning Detection", "stiType": "CONFERENCE_PAPER", "distribution": "PUBLIC", "submittedDate": "2013-08-20T15:54:00.0000000+00:00", "authorAffiliations": [{"sequence": 0, "submissionId": 20020023936, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Bocippio, Dennis J."}, "organization": {"name": "NASA Marshall Space Flight Center", "location": "Huntsville, AL United States"}}, "id": "b7f2742b31214089855926ef262dc4e0"}, {"sequence": 1, "submissionId": 20020023936, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Christian, Hugh J."}, "organization": {"name": "NASA Marshall Space Flight Center", "location": "Huntsville, AL United States"}}, "id": "ebdf51c6982a447d8471a45ca3a4c30e"}, {"sequence": 2, "submissionId": 20020023936, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Arnold, James E."}, "organization": {}}, "id": "d995498530884ad895c3b480981097d7"}], "stiTypeDetails": "Conference Paper", "technicalReviewType": "TECHNICAL_REVIEW_TYPE_NONE", "modified": "2011-08-22T00:00:00.0000000+00:00", "id": 20020023936, "created": "2013-08-20T15:54:00.0000000+00:00", "center": {"code": "MSFC", "name": "Marshall Space Flight Center", "id": "a589fc1e68af409f9d2214bb08863d11"}, "onlyAbstract": true, "sensitiveInformation": 2, "abstract": "The future of satellite-based optical lightning detection, beyond the end of the current TRMM mission, is discussed. Opportunities for new low-earth orbit missions are reviewed. The potential for geostationary observations is significant; such observations provide order-of-magnitude gains in sampling and data efficiency over existing satellite convective observations. The feasibility and performance (resolution, sensitivity) of geostationary measurements using current technology is discussed. In addition to direct and continuous hemispheric observation of lighting, geostationary measurements have the potential (through data assimilation) to dramatically improve short and medium range forecasts, offering benefits to prediction of NOx productions and/or vertical transport.", "isLessonsLearned": false, "disseminated": "METADATA_ONLY", "meetings": [{"country": "Germany", "submissionId": 20020023936, "name": "8th Scientific Assembly of IAMAS", "location": "Munich", "id": "31b66077c4d74df29012d846517c6714", "startDate": "2001-07-13T00:00:00.0000000+00:00"}], "publications": [{"submissionId": 20020023936, "id": "0b14644598da46228d14b1abd30ba190", "publicationDate": "2001-01-01T00:00:00.0000000+00:00"}], "status": "CURATED", "related": [], "downloads": [], "downloadsAvailable": false, "index": "submissions-2022-09-30-06-07"}